e Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014The Rem\nington Arms Co., Inc., controlled by\nE. I. Dupont de Nemours Co., re\nported today 1937 net Income of $1,\n509,804, equal to 17 cents a share\nan the common stock, against $1,100,\n905, or 14 cents a share in 1936.\nAmerican Radiator.\nAmerican Radiator Sanitary I\nCorp. reported for the year ended De\ncember 31 consolidated net income of\n$7,205,510, against $7,344,514 in 1936.\nThe profits were equal after divi\ndend requirements on the preferred\nstock of 68 cents a share of common\nstock, compared with 70 cents a share\nin 1936.\nHinde Dauch Paper Co. reported\nnet profit for 1937 of $1,451,636, equal\nto $3.53 per share of common stock,\ncompared with $1,246,543, or $2.86 in\nthe previous year. Company's plants\nare in the Midwest, East and South.\nSouthern California Edison.\nSouthern California Edison Co.,\nLtd., excluding subsidiaries, for 1937\nreported preliminary net income of\n$12,136,162, before allowing for the\nFederal surtax, equal to $2.22 a share\non the common stock, compared with\n$12,760,559, or $2.42 a share, in 1936.\nSouthern Pacific.\nSouthern Pacific Transportation\nSystem for 1937 reported net income\nof $756,793, equal to 20 cents a share\non the capital stock, against $14,\n503,330, or $3.84 a share, in 1936.\nDecember net income amounted to\n$365,808, compared with $4,052,624\nin the comparable 1936 month.\nErie Railroad.\nErie Railroad reported for 12 months\nended December 31 net loss of $433,\n293, against net income of $2,195,014.\nequal to $4.58 a share of first preferred\nstock, in 1936. For December the\nsystem had a net loss of $1,043,604,\nagainst net Income of $177,836 in 1936.\nChicago. Milwaukee.\nChicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul Pa\ncific Railroad reported for the 12\nmonths ended December 31 net loss\nof $14,221,271, against net loss of $13,\n196.108 in 1936. For December there\nwas a net loss of $1,414,803. against\nnet loss of $226,263 in December, 1936.\n\nBUILDING AWARDS\nABOVE 1937 LEVELS'\ni\nSeveral Large Housing Projects\nContribute Importantly to\nWeek\u2019s Increase.\nBt the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014Several\nlarge housing developments con-;\ntributed importantly to an increase in\nengineering construction awards com\npared with last year, the weekly re\nport of- the Engineering News-Record\nshowed today\nThe total, covering the week ended\nTuesday, was $45,001,000 against $42.\n558.000 in the 1937 period and $54,\n831.000 in the preceding week.\nPrivate projects accounted for $21,\n077.000 of the total against $17,860,- j\n000 in the 1937 week and $30,556,000\nin the preceding week.\nA $4,000,000 residential development\nin Springfield, Pa was listed, along\nwith housing projects in Richmond, i\nHouston Baltimore and Gicnrock, j\nN. J., involving $800,000 to $1,000 000 i\neach.\nPublic projects again were lower!\nthan last year, totaling $23,924,000;\nagainst $24,698,000 m the 1937 period\nand $24,275,000 in the preceding week, i\n\nLARGE GAINS REPORTED\nBY AMERICAN FIDELITY\n81 tclal Dispatch to Th\u00ab 8tar.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014The report\nDf American Fidelity Casualty Co.\nFor the year ended December 31, 1937,\nshows premiums earned of $2,983,\n127.12, compared with $2,661,039.51 in\n1936.\nNet earned operating profit amount\ned to $138,266.18, equal to about $1.38\ni share on the average number of\nshares outstanding during the year,\nrhis result represented an increase of\n$42.067.23, or 44 per cent over the 1936\nfigure of $69,198.95.\nProfit from underwriting was $105,\n420.74, compared with $63,677.46 the\nprevious year: income from invest\nments of $32,845.44, compared with\n$32,521.49. There was a net deprecia\ntion of $1,557.81 in value of invest\nment, compared with $46,390.14 ap\npreciation on December 31, 1936.\nTotal admitted assets as at Decem\noer 31, 1937, were $2,552,688.40, com\npared with $1,739,303,23, an increase\nsf $813,385.17 over December 31, 1936.\nPREMIUM RECORD SET\nBY AMERICAN MUTUAL\nSrtclal Dispatch to Tht Star.\nBOSTON, Mass., Feb. 17.\u2014The\nAmerican Mutual Liability Insurance\n3o. of Boston marked the flfty-flrst\ncalendar year of its history in 1937 by\nshowing an increase of 28 per cent in\nits premium writings over the 1936\ntotal, the business of the year amount\ning to $27,646,624.\nPremiums for the third successive\nyear reached the highest levels In the\nhistory of the company. Assets, re\nserves and surplus increased corre\nspondingly.\nAt the end of the year 1937 the\npolicyholders\u2019 surplus equaled $5,423,\n393.76 and the assets $34,866,615.64.\nSHORT-TERM SECURITIES.\n(Reported by Smith, Barney Co.)\nBid. Offer.\nkmer Tel ft Tel 5%s 1943. 113% 113%\nSuburn Auto Co 4%s 1939 18% 10\nkustin ft Northwest Ss 1041. 80 92\n3aldwin Loco Works 5a 1940 101%\nCalif Packing Corp 5s 1040 104 104%\nCentral Foundry 6s 1941 102\nChesa Ohio Rwy 5s 1939. 104% 105\nContainer Corp 5s 1943 84% 89\nCuba North Rwys 6%s, 1042 40 41\nDelaware ft Hudson 4s 1043 51 52\nEdison Elec Ilium 4s 1939 102% 103\n3eneral Pub Serv 5%s 1939. 97%\nDrand Rap Ind 4%s 1941 _ 108%\nHouston Oil 5%s 1940 99% 100%\nIllinois Steel 4%s 1040 107%\nInter Merc Marine 6s 1041 40% 42\nInter Tel ft Tel 4%s 1039 86 86%\nJaclede Oas Liaht 6s 1030 85 87\nJake Erie ft West 5s 1941. 95%\nJehlgh Val Ter P.y as 1941. __ 71%\nJouis ft Nash R R 4s 1940 102% 102%\nMichigan Cent R R 4s 1940 100\nilldland R R of N J 5s 1040 leys 19%\nHilw ft North R R 4%s 1039 51 74%\nHew Tork Tel Co 4%s 1939. 106y\u00ab 106%\n\u2022ennsylvania Co 3%s 1041. 102 103%\n\u00bbenn-Dixie Cement 6s 1941. 79 80\n\u2022enna R R Co 4a 1943 108% 111\n\u2019fella Balt ft Wash 4f 194.3 108% 110%\nllo Grande West 4s 1939 43 44\nrerm RR As St L 4 Vis 1939 105\nrexas ft N Orleans 5s 1943. 104%\nfanadlum Corp 5s 1941_ 84 86\nWarner Bros 6s 1939 71 72%\nRSnMftAfeiM: TO TO\nt\nEmployment in Leading Industries\n1923.1925= 100 IASS WON MMX NUMKRS IV MOUSTWB. MC. 1917\nMeat Packing Men's Clothing Women's Clothing Iron end Steel\n\nWoolen Milk\nR. Agricultural Implements\nOP lAIOt STATISTICS _\nUSED AUTO JAM\nEASES SLIGHTLY\nIncrease in New-Car Sales\nAlso Spurs Hopes of\nMotor Industry.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDETROIT, Feb. 17.\u2014A moderate\nsasing of the used-car Jam along with\nin increase in new-car distribution\nluring the last fortnight brought en\ncouragement to maker and merchan\nliser in the automobile industry and\ninspired renewed hope among the\nexecutives in the manufacturing and\nsales divisions that the bottom of the\npresent curtailment of car buying has\noeen passed.\nMost observers In automotive trade\ncircles are cautiously predicting an up\nward movement of factory activity\naround March 1, based upon their\nbelief that even a moderate seasonal\nactivity in used ui>its will turn new-cai\nproduction totals definitely upward.\nInventories Reduced.\nOn the basis of present activity in\nthe assembly plants, February output\nshould come close to 250.000 cars\nand trucks, which the manufacturers\nemphasize is far from a complete\nsuspension of work. On the other\nband, no producer currently Is work\ning on a full-time schedule.\nOne agency that has made a de\ntailed survey of the dealer units\nthroughout the United States reports\nthat with few exceptions these out\nlets are beginning to reduce inven\ntories of both used and new cars.\nSome, the advices indicate, have ob\ntained encouraging results from a re\nadjustment of prices on used vehicles.\nWhile not belittling the efforts of\nindividual dealers in chipping at the\naccumulation of second-hand cars,\nthe trade generally still is hopeful\nsome large-scale plan of reducing the\niealer stocks will be worked out\nthrough combined action of producer\nand distributor and thus reopen a\nsizable new-car market.\nLooks tor Upturn.\nSome sales executives of the major\nproducing units look for a sizable\nbulge in factory activity in March.\nApril and May. a few venturing as\nfar as to say these months will bet\n:er the showing of the same periods\nbf 1937. All are agreed a substantial\n\u2022eduction in the used-car accumula\ntion will be reflected immediately in\nttew-acr assemblies, regardless of any\nbther conditions that might currently\nbe contributing to the curtailment of\nbuying power.\nThe hope of matching 1937 in ag\ngregate assemblies, however, is\nSwindling rapidly, and most compe\ntent observers have placed their 1938\ntotal estimate around the 4,000,000\nmark. The aggregate for last year\nwas slightly above 5,000,000 units.\nCOLORADO FUEL IRON\nREPORTS $48,939 LOSS\nBr the AssocUted Press\nDENVER. Peb. 17.\u2014The Colorado\nFuel Iron Corp. arid its subsidiary\ncompanies operated at a net loss of\n$48,939 during the six-month period\n;nded December 31, 1937, the com\npany reported.\nThe company had reported a net\nprofit of $442,080 for the third quar\nter last year, ended September 30.\n1937. This was more than erased, the\ncompany reported today, by a loss of\n$491,019 for the final quarter ended\nDecember 31.\nOn December 31, the statement said,\nthere .were 563,620 shares of common\nstock outstanding.\nP. W. V. RAILWAY ASKS\nR. F. C. LOAN APPROVAL\nB1 the Associated Press.\nThe Pittsburgh West Virginia\nRailway Co. asked the Interstate\nCommerce Commission today to ap\nprove its application lor a $500,080\nReconstruction Finance Corp. loan.\nMost of the proposed loan would\nbe used to meet fixed charges matur\nng April 1. These amount to $468,625.\nThe railroad already owes the R.\nP. C. $3,725,207. It has pledged col\nlateral which it said had a value in\nexcess of $8,000,000. No additional\ncollateral would be offered for the\n(500,000 loan.\nHAND-TO-MOUTH BASIS\nIN STEEL TO CONTINUE\nBr the Associated Press.\nCLEVELAND, Feb. 17.\u2014Daily Metal\nTrade says:\n\u201cHand-to-mouth steel buying is ex\npected to continue until the business\noutlook has been clarified.\n\u201cAnnouncement of second-quarter\nprioes, looked for momentarily, is seen\nas helping to clear the fog now envel\noping the market. Indications are the\ncurrent price schedule will be extended\nunchanged, the recent' reduction in\ncold-rolled sheets being confined to\nthat, product.\u201d\nADVERTISING INDEX OFF.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17 G45).\u2014The\nmonthly Printers\u2019 Ink index of news\npaper advertising showed a decline of\nB.O per cent in January from the\nsame month of 1937, and a decline of\n16.7 per cent under December, ad\nlusted for the usual seasonal trend.\nLife Insurance\nIn January Lags\nBehind Last Year\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014New life in\nsurance for January was 12.1 per cent\nunder the same month last year, the\nAssociation of Life Insurance Presi\ndents reported.\nThe association, in its monthly re\nport to the Department of Commerce,\nshowed new paid-for life Insurance\namounting to $589,185,000 for Janu\nary, compared with $670,390,000 for\nthe same month in 1937.\nThe report includes 40 companies\nhaving 82 per cent of the total life\ninsurance outstanding in all United\nStates legal reserve companies.\nINVESTING COMPANIES\nNEW YORK, Feb 17 .^.\u2014Investment\nBankers\u2019 Conference Inc.\n(Noon quotations.)\nBid Asked.\nAdmin Fd 2d Ine 11.49 12.22\nAm Business Shrs new_ 3.77 3.81\nAm Gen Eq Inc _ 80 .HR\nAm Ins Stocks 4.50 fi.no\nBancamer Blair _ 3.75 *.75\nBankers Nat Inv. Oorp 2.00 2.825\nRasic Industry _ 3.08\nBoston Fund inc _ 14 88 15.HR\nBroad Si Inv _ 22.28 23.81\nBullock Fund _ _12.5n 13.825\nCorporate Trust _ 2.08 _\nCorporate Trust A A_ 2.oi _\nCorp Tr A A mfld _ 7.44 _\nCorp Tr Acctim Sf r_ 7 01 _\ni Corp Tr Acc Mod _ 7 44 _\nI Cumulative Tr Bh _ 4.20\nDepos Bk Sh N Y \u201dA\"-._ 1.54 _\nDepos Ins Shrs \"A\"_ 2.79 _\nDepos Ins Shrs \"B\u201d_ 2.57 _\nDiversified Tr C_ 3.30\n1 Dividend Shrs _ l.lfi 1.25\nEquity Corp S3 pf_ 24.00 27.00\nFidelity Fund Inc_ 17.81 19.24\nFirst Boston Oorp_ 13.375 14 875\nFiscal Fund Bk Sh_ 2.48 2.72\nFiscal Fund Ins_ 3.11 3.42\nFixed Trust 8h A _ fi.40\