_ 5.27 I\"\nSuper of Am Tr D _ 5 27\nSupervised Shrs .III 8.71 9 68\"\nTrustee Stand Inv C_ 2.18\nTrustee Stand Inv D _2.13\nTrusteed Am Bk \u201dB\u201d_ .80 .67\"\nTrusteed Industry Shrs_ .87 .95\nWellington Fund _ 12.49 13 77\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 17 MV\u2014Most Eu\nropean currencies interrupted their for\nward march in terms of the dollar today.\nA decline of A of a cent in the pound\nsterling was regarded in some banking\ncircles as due more to conversion of re\ncently acquired sterling balances into gold\nrather than a change of viewpoint toward\ndomestic inflationary tendencies.\nDeclines of .(K)Vi of a cent and .03 of\na cent, respectively, were noted In the\nSwiss franc and guilder. The French\nfrancz and belga were unchanged.\nNoon rates follow: Great Britain in\ndollars, others in cents. Great Britain\ndemand. 5.03: cables. 5.03: 80-day bills\n3.02'.,. France, demand, 3.20',; cables.\n3.20,. Italy, demand. 5.20'*; cables,\n5.2 b '-a\nDemands\u2014Belgium. 17.03; Germany\nfree. 40.55: registered. 20.05; travel, 4.40;\nHolland. 50.12; Norway. 25.28: Sweden,\n25.04; Denmark. 22.47: Finland. 2722;\nSwitzerland, 23.30: Spain. unquoted;\nPortugal. 4.58; Greece. .924.; Poland,\n19.02; Czechoslovakia. 3.52s,; Yugoslavia.\n5.30: Austria. 19.00n: Hungary. 19.95;\nRumania. .70: Argentina. 33.55n; Brazil\nfree), 5.85n: Toklo. 29.00: Shanghai.\n29.85; Hong Kong. 31.50; Mexico City.\n27.82. Montreal in New York. 100.061,;\nNew York In Montreal. 99.934,.\nn Nominal.\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK.\nCHICAGO. -Feb. 17 UP (D. S. Dept. Agr.V\n\u2014Hogs. 14.000. including 3.000 direct;\nfully 10-15 higher than Wednesday's aver\nage; active at advance: bulk good and\nchoice 150-220 lbs.. 8.65-8.90; top. 8.95;\n230-270 lbs.. 8.20-8.65: 280-350 lbs..\n7.75-8.15; good medium weight and heavy\npacking sows. 7.00-7.25; light butcher\nkinds up to 7.40.\nCattle, 6.000; calves. 1.200; steer and\nyearling trade much less active than Wed\nnesday but steady on early rounds to\nshipper and order buyers; big packers\nbidding 15-25 lower; prospects steady to\nweak: killing quality less desirable, bulk\nselling at 8.25 down: best steers held\nground 9.50; heifers In moderate supply,\nsteady: beef cows weak, but cutter grades\nsteady; bulls steady to weak: vealers steady\nto 50 lower; light,kinds showing decline;\noutside on weighty sausage bulla. 0.86: se\nlected vcal#rs to 11.50. but mostly 11.00\ndown.\nSheep. 10.000; none direct; late Wed\nnesday. fat lambs weak to 10 lower than\nTuesday: top, 7.60: bulk, including 96-100\n1b. averages and best Colorados. 7.25-40;\ntoday's lamb trade opening 10-15 higher\nat 7.35-7.60: best held 7.65 upward: in\ndications steady on sheep.\nNEW YORK SUGAR.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 17 MV\u2014Irregular\nprice movements occurred in the sugar\nfutures market today.\nThe No. 3 contract, after declining 1\nto 2 points under Increased selling by\nproducing interests, rallied on renewed\ncovering and trade buying. The No. 4\neased under liquidation and trade gelling.\nMarch No. 3 sold up from 2.25 to 2.28\nand July from 2.28 to 2.30. leaving the\nlist at 2 p.m. unchanged to l point net\nlower. July No. 4 sold off to 1.68 and\nSeptember to 1.10. or 44 to 1 oolnt net\nlower.\nOlobe-Wernicke Co.\u20141937 common\n\u25a0hare earning* wen $1.70 again** $141.\nA\nFIRST FISCAL FUND\nAssets of $1,997,824.79 Are\nCovered by 734,877\nShares.\nBrecltl Dispatch to Tha Star.\nPHILADELPHIA, Feb. 17.\u2014Tota\nassets of Fiscal Fund, Inc., on De\ncember 31, 1937, were *1,997,834.7!\nand outstanding shares 734,877, ac\ncording to the first annual report o;\nthe fund Just issued. The report\ncovers the period from January 31\n1937, when the fund began opera\ntions, to December 31. Of the assel\ntotal *335.789.40 was applicable tc\n343.155 shares of the bank stock se\nries and *1,163.035.39 applicable tc\n392,722 share of the insurance stock\nseries.\nIncome account shows distributable\nfunds after deduction for expense*\nof (25,294.65 on shares of the bank\nstock series and *36,727.63 on share*\nof the insurance stock series. During\nthe year dividends totaling *24.898.64\nwere paid on the bank shares anc\n(36,120.98 on the insurance shares\npayment on the bank shares totaling\ncents per share and on the in\nsurance shares 9 Vi cents per share\nIn addition, stock dividends totaling\n5 per cent were paid on each clast\nof shares.\nFunds of the bank stock series art\ninvested in shares of 21 banks anc\nthose of the insurance stock aerie;\nin shares of 24 insurance companies\neach of which is briefly outlined it\nthe report. Commenting on these it\nthe report, F. D. Crosby, president\nsaid: \"The average age of the 2\nbanks in the portfolio of Fiscal Funt\nis 82 years, and the average age o\nthe 24 insurance companies is 8!\nyears. The banks have paid divi\ndends in every year for an averagt\nof 65 continuous years, and the in\nsurance companies have done so foi\nan average of 61 continuous years.\u201d\nPrior to issuance of shares of Fisca\nFund the sponsoring company. Trans\ncontinent Shares Corp., issued vari\nous series of deposited bank share;\nand deposited Insurance shares, be\nginning In 1928. Offerings of thes<\nshares were discontinued with incep\ntion of Fiscal Fund.\nJOBLESS FUND MOUNTS.\nDeposits by States of their unem\nployment trust funds in the Treasury\ntotal (434.121.816 to date in the fisca\nyear, offset by withdrawals of *38,\n350.000.\nTotal for 5 Days Declines\nSlightly From Previous\nFull Week.\nBt the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014Although\nbank Clearings for most cities ware\non a flve-day basis during the\nlatest period, total volume was only\nslightly under that of the preceding\nfull week. The unfavorable contrast\nwith the totals for the corresponding\nperiod of the previous year, however,\ncontinued for the 14th straight time.\nThe aggregate for 22 leading cities\nof the United States for the week\nended Wednesday, February 16, ac\ncording to Dun Bradstreet, Inc.,\namounted to *4,297,187,000. This com\npared with *5,578.656,000 for the same\n1937 week, giving a decrease of 23\nper cent. In the year-to-year compari\nson for the preceding week there was\na drop of 23.1 per cent.\nThe flve-day turnover at New York\nwas *2,564,498,000, a drop of 25 2 per\ncent from the *3.428.949,000 for the\nsimilar 1937 period, while the outside\ncenters furnished a total of *1,732.\n689.000, which was 19.4 per cent under\nthe *2,149,707,000 recorded last year.\nClearings for the latest period drop\nped *25,629,000 from the total of the\nweek preceding. Between the same\ntwo weeks of 1937 there was a loss of\n*42,210,000.\nA gain of 14.8 per cent at Louisville\nwas the only increase reported at out\nside centers this week. The more im\nportant declines included: Detroit,\n29.3 per cent; Cleveland, 26.2 per cent;\nSt. Louts, 25.7 per cent; Boston, 25.1\nper cent: Chicago, 24 3 per cent: San\nFrancisco, 22.8 per cent, and Pitts\nburgh, 20.4 per cent,\ni Bank clearings at leading cities, to\ngether with percentage comparisons\nwith a year ago, follow. Also the daily\naverage bank clearings for the months\nof December, January and February\nto date:\nweek p\u00bbr\n(flvedtys! cent\nFeb. 16. 1938. Chinee.\n_ i OOO omitted\n|o\u00bb*on $183,588 \u201425.1\nPhiladelphia _ 320.firm \u201413 .3\n?uflalo 27.800 \u201425 8\nIttsbureh _ 103 807 \u2014\"O 4.\nCleveland_ 08.732 20 3\nCincinnati _ 51.079 \u201410 5\nBaltimore _ 00 508 \u201411 1\nRichmond _ _ _ 34 '3 _ 5 <t\nAtlanta _ 49.700 \u201417 4,\nNew Orleans_ _ 39.2.311 2 4,\nChicago _ 245,200 \u00b04 3\nDetroit 77.689 \u201429!.3\nSt Louis _ _ 71 977 _\"5 7\nLouisville _ 34,084 _ 14 8\nMinneapolis_ 50 030 \u201415 5\nKansas City _ 74 102 177\nOmaha _ 23.404 \u201415 7\nDallas _ 43 508 \u201410.3\nSan Francisco_ 120 600 _2\" s\nPortland. Ore*._ 23.748 \u201414 1\nSeattle- 29,324 \u201418 4;\nTotal $1,732,889\nNew York_ 2,564 498 \u201425 3\nTotal all-$4,297,187 -^234J\nAeerare Dally.\nFebruary (to date)_ *735.599 \u201429 8\nJanuary 871918 \u2014in 9\nDecember _ 992,508 \u201417.3\nPULLMAN, INC., ORDERS\n37'/2-CENT dividend;\nL By the Associated Press.\n1 CHICAGO, Feb. 17.\u2014Directors of\nPullman, Inc., yesterday voted a divi\ndend of 37\u20192 cents per share on tha\ncapital stock, payable March 15 to\nstock of record February 25. Last!\nDecember 21 the company paid a\nspecial of *1.25. which brought total\n1 payments in 1937 to *2.75\n1 1\nTO PURCHASE\nOR REFINANCE\nINTEREST Your saving* bar* aro\nIt low OS 5% protected by Federal\nInsuraaeo up to $5,000\nNO COMMISSIONS.\nNO RENEWALS.\nEasy Monthly Payments as tow as $7.SO pot f 1,000\nCOLUMBIA\nV BUILDING ASSOCIATION\n716 11th St N. W.\nOpposite Palais Royal\nMonthly Payment\nREAL ESTATE\nLOANS\nOn Improved Property\nINTEREST\nNo Renewals\nConsult Real Estate Department\nAmerican Security\nAND TRUST COMPANY\nHam omci: Fifteenth St. and Pennsylvania Are.\nBrandt Offices\n7th and Mass. Ave., N. W. Seventh and E St., S. W.\nEighth and H Sts.. N. E. 1140 Fifteenth St., N. W.","height":"31308","width":"22380"}}
